### Power Conserving Path Placement Strategy (PCPPS)
* **Presenter**: Ron Bonica
* **Discussion**:
  * Ron Bonica presented an updated strategy to optimize network power consumption during low-demand periods by concentrating traffic on the smallest set of links and powering down idle resources.
  * Recent draft updates replaced "power utilization" with "potential power savings" (the difference between active and sleeping power consumption) based on feedback from Carlos Pignataro, acknowledging that sleeping interfaces may still consume power on some hardware architectures.
  * The draft's status was changed from Informational to Proposed Standard due to its dependency on a linked LSR draft that defines IGP power information advertisements.
  * The Session Chair advised maintaining close coordination with the GREEN Working Group. Tony Li confirmed that coordination has occurred and that their work is aligned; the LSR/TEAS work focuses on compact IGP encoding, while the GREEN WG addresses broader YANG-based modeling.
  * Zafar Ali raised concerns about the complexity of low-level power modeling, suggesting that simpler interface- or laser-level attributes might be more practical to implement and deploy. Ron Bonica noted that power savings data can be derived programmatically or through manual configuration based on vendor spec sheets.
