### Multicast Traffic Engineering (MC-TE)
* **Presenter**: Kireeti Kompella
* **Discussion**:
  * Kireeti Kompella proposed applying the junction concept from MP-TE to Point-to-Multipoint (P2MP) LSPs. Rather than signaling multiple sub-LSPs (RFC 4875), which creates significant Path State Block (PSB) and Resv State Block (RSV) overhead, MC-TE introduces a Junction State Block (JSB) to collapse state on replication nodes and reduce signaling churn during leaf joins/leaves.
  * Andrew Stone pointed out that this concept overlaps significantly with SR Replication Segments (SR P2MP Policies) already defined in SPRING/BGP/PCEP and cautioned that DAG-based multicast optimization must carefully address complex loop-prevention issues.
  * Changzhou asked if the proposal supports Steiner vs. non-Steiner tree computations. Kireeti Kompella clarified that the computation is orthogonal; once the tree shape is determined, JSB is used for efficient signaling.
  * Lou Burger recalled that the sub-LSP concept in RFC 4875 allowed single-PSB state collapsing as a standard compromise for faster implementation. He suggested investigating whether the desired junction behavior can be achieved with minimal modifications to the existing sub-LSP protocols rather than creating new ones.

### Carrying 5G Network Slice Identifiers in IP Headers for QoS Assurance Beyond the 3GPP Domain
* **Presenter**: Changzhou (on behalf of co-authors Jerry and Gong Yu)
* **Discussion**:
  * Changzhou presented the slides [13 Carrying 5G Network Slice Identifiers in IP Headers for QoS Assurance Beyond the 3GPP-Managed Domain](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-teas-13-carrying-5g-network-slice-identifiers-in-ip-headers-for-qos-assurance-beyond-the-3gpp-managed-domain-01).
  * The draft proposes mapping the 3GPP 32-bit slice identifier (S-NSSAI) into an IPv6 Hop-by-Hop (HbH) option (leveraging the 6man network resource option format) as packets transition from the UPF into the IP backbone. This allows backbone routers to enforce slice-specific QoS policies.
  * Nathan raised concerns about the overhead of adding 12 bytes to packet headers and questioned whether mapping the traffic to simpler QoS slice types rather than propagating the full slice ID would be a more practical approach. The presenter agreed to follow up on the mailing list.

### High-Performance Computing / AI (HPC/AI) Data Models
* **Presenter**: Quan
* **Discussion**:
  * Quan presented three new drafts defining YANG models to map HPC/AI scheduling metadata, service intents, and tunnel realization.
  * The Session Chair noted that while the scheduling metadata and service intent models likely fall outside the scope of the TEAS WG, the third draft on tunnel realization (augmenting TE tunnels) could be discussed here. The presenter was encouraged to socialize the work on the mailing list.

